          <avActivityHighlights>Wet snow requires caution.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of new snow and wind, wind slabs formed in the last few days at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of warming there will be a gradual increase in the avalanche danger. On very steep slopes the moist avalanches can be released naturally and reach medium size in isolated cases. &lt;br/&gt; Individual avalanche prone locations are to be found on very steep shady slopes above approximately 2600 m. Avalanches can be released, mostly by large loads and reach medium size.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Below approximately 2500 m a little snow is lying. The spring-like weather conditions will give rise to rapid moistening of the snowpack. The surface of the snowpack will only just freeze and will soften quickly. &lt;br/&gt; Steep west, north and east facing slopes above approximately 2500 m: Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the old snowpack.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The avalanche danger will persist.</tendencyComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
